00:08:18,701 --> 00:08:20,261
and build basically the game on that.

152
00:08:20,521 --> 00:08:22,441
So that's the writing, it has three points.

153
00:08:22,561 --> 00:08:24,542
I will start by evocative writing,

154
00:08:25,262 --> 00:08:26,582
which is very useful tool,

155
00:08:26,902 --> 00:08:29,443
where we don't use that much in games,

156
00:08:29,823 --> 00:08:30,863
and that's a shame I think.

157
00:08:32,944 --> 00:08:36,327
If you see this picture, it's a still life, it's a bit boring.

158
00:08:36,507 --> 00:08:39,310
It's called Breakfast Table with Blackberry Pie.

159
00:08:40,691 --> 00:08:46,277
But if you look a bit more closely and you think of this painting as a scene in a game,

160
00:08:46,677 --> 00:08:49,940
it's actually very entertaining and very thrilling.

161
00:08:53,324 --> 00:08:56,347
glass broken on the left, is it the result of a fight

162
00:08:56,367 --> 00:08:57,909
or does it contain poison?

163
00:08:58,950 --> 00:09:00,712
Why are things left out like that?

164
00:09:00,752 --> 00:09:02,734
There's a cane in the middle, you see,

165
00:09:03,054 --> 00:09:04,836
and it hides something, maybe it's a weapon.

166
00:09:05,176 --> 00:09:07,279
And the thing on the right, is it a clock?

167
00:09:07,559 --> 00:09:10,242
Maybe it is a time travel device.

168
00:09:10,642 --> 00:09:12,464
And the key, what does the key open?

169
00:09:13,745 --> 00:09:16,586
interesting things that happen by evocation.

170
00:09:17,106 --> 00:09:19,647
And I use that a lot in Reigns.

171
00:09:19,747 --> 00:09:21,828
If you take this card, for example,

172
00:09:21,848 --> 00:09:25,829
you got the unknown body, you got the hands missing,

173
00:09:26,229 --> 00:09:28,350
you got the garrison and the dungeon.

174
00:09:28,650 --> 00:09:32,911
So all this creates some sort of structure to the whole game

175
00:09:32,951 --> 00:09:36,852
that we really heavily worked,

176
00:09:38,833 --> 00:09:42,234
that we used a lot because this evocates

177
00:09:42,815 --> 00:09:45,121
the kingdom that's behind the game.

178
00:09:46,324 --> 00:09:50,133
And that was very important to really build on this.

179
00:09:51,290 --> 00:09:52,491
about comedy and rhythm.

180
00:09:54,932 --> 00:09:58,054
We quickly discovered that there was a very strong

181
00:09:58,134 --> 00:10:02,256
comical gap between the decision you take

182
00:10:02,457 --> 00:10:05,538
that impact your kingdom, you send people to the death,

183
00:10:05,578 --> 00:10:08,200
you deal with earthquakes, you deal with a lot

184
00:10:08,240 --> 00:10:11,462
of easy stuff actually, and the way you have to deal

185
00:10:11,482 --> 00:10:14,804
with this by swiping, which is like the most casual way

186
00:10:14,884 --> 00:10:16,584
of dealing with a situation if you want.

187
00:10:17,065 --> 00:10:19,486
And that creates a gap that's very comical.

188
00:10:19,566 --> 00:10:22,787
And only that, only creating very serious cards,

189
00:10:23,128 --> 00:10:24,968
was actually very funny for the player.

190
00:10:25,008 --> 00:10:28,490
And player were like, well, how do I do that?

191
00:10:28,570 --> 00:10:32,452
And the fact that the only options were swiping

192
00:10:33,292 --> 00:10:35,313
makes it very funny.

193
00:10:35,693 --> 00:10:37,995
And we basically just built on this.

194
00:10:38,375 --> 00:10:40,056
hiding more and more weird card,

195
00:10:40,116 --> 00:10:43,720
more and more with unfathomable consequences

196
00:10:43,740 --> 00:10:47,643
that generally bring you to your death very quickly.

197
00:10:48,344 --> 00:10:52,988
As some sort of illustration of a very casual power

198
00:10:53,329 --> 00:10:55,311
that just deal with binary decisions,

199
00:10:55,731 --> 00:10:58,734
is bad and can quickly become sore.

200
00:10:59,314 --> 00:11:03,058
So, also an important thing for the writing of this

201
00:11:03,518 --> 00:11:04,539
was the rhythm.

202
00:11:04,680 --> 00:11:06,481
The rhythm in the game is very important

203
00:11:06,902 --> 00:11:11,266
and it took me some time to learn to do that rhythm.

204
00:11:12,287 --> 00:11:14,389
The pace of the game is very quick

205
00:11:14,789 --> 00:11:18,153
and you have to go from tac-tac-tac and boom you die.

206
00:11:20,635 --> 00:11:23,717
I had to keep in everything I wrote for the games

207
00:11:23,757 --> 00:11:25,999
this sort of very strong rhythm

208
00:11:26,619 --> 00:11:28,841
that Jenny finished with these dafts

209
00:11:28,901 --> 00:11:31,262
that are like a clash that just

210
00:11:32,183 --> 00:11:34,805
breaks you in your pace.

211
00:11:36,966 --> 00:11:41,890
So making that sort of thing was difficult for me.

212
00:11:42,980 --> 00:11:44,582
to find the right tone for the game.

213
00:11:44,942 --> 00:11:48,287
I had to train myself to write games cards.

214
00:11:48,687 --> 00:11:50,470
There's no easy way to do that.

215
00:11:50,590 --> 00:11:52,192
So I wrote 770 cards in the game.

216
00:11:52,212 --> 00:11:53,754
And it's really only after the first.

217
00:11:58,320 --> 00:12:02,501
200 cards but I had the tone, I had the way to play

218
00:12:02,561 --> 00:12:07,662
with my mechanics if you want, and how to define

219
00:12:07,982 --> 00:12:09,443
the sentences so they make sense.

220
00:12:10,543 --> 00:12:13,644
I studied French literature and we like to make

221
00:12:13,884 --> 00:12:17,045
long sentences, so it was very painful for me to do that.

222
00:12:18,725 --> 00:12:20,566
So probabilistic driven narratives,

223
00:12:20,606 --> 00:12:23,206
so that's also very painful, I'm sorry about that.

224
00:12:24,707 --> 00:12:28,148
So, as I told you, players started to create

225
00:12:28,168 --> 00:12:30,328
their own narratives within the game.

226
00:12:30,888 --> 00:12:32,329
So we decided to encourage that,

227
00:12:32,549 --> 00:12:38,010
and that was difficult because we also needed

228
00:12:38,070 --> 00:12:40,150
to keep the flow of the game.

229
00:12:40,991 --> 00:12:43,871
The flow of the game is very important in ranks.

230
00:12:44,151 --> 00:12:47,372
You really have to be able to play hundreds of cards

231
00:12:47,432 --> 00:12:49,472
in the sessions of 20 minutes, for example,

232
00:12:49,753 --> 00:12:51,973
which is generally the time you spend on the game.

233
00:12:52,553 --> 00:12:52,633
And...

234
00:12:53,934 --> 00:12:56,555
That was basically creating a narrative

235
00:12:56,615 --> 00:12:59,736
